File: platform/browser-extension/src/browser-commands/extension-commands.ts, lines 350-458.

The bug: The outer Promise.race (line 450) races injectPromise against timeoutPromise. When timeoutPromise wins (SCRIPT_TIMEOUT_MS = 25s), the catch block at line 456 calls sendErrorResult but never cleans up the page globals __lastExecResult and __lastExecAsync. The cleanup code at lines 424-437 only runs when the inner async-wait loop (EXEC_MAX_ASYNC_WAIT_MS) times out.

Fix approach: In the catch block (line 456), before calling sendErrorResult, add a best-effort cleanup call identical to lines 425-437:

await chrome.scripting.executeScript({
  target: { tabId },
  world: 'MAIN',
  func: () => {
    const ot = (globalThis as Record<string, unknown>).__openTabs as Record<string, unknown> | undefined;
    if (ot) {
      delete ot.__lastExecResult;
      delete ot.__lastExecAsync;
    }
  },
}).catch(() => {});

Note: tabId is declared at line 341 and is in scope for the catch block. The cleanup must be best-effort (.catch(() => {})) because the tab may have been closed.

To avoid duplication, consider extracting the cleanup script into a shared helper function used by both cleanup sites (lines 424-437 and the new catch block).

File: platform/browser-extension/src/browser-commands/cookie-commands.ts, lines 77-91.

The bug: chrome.cookies.remove returns null when no matching cookie is found, but the code at line 86-87 unconditionally returns { deleted: true } regardless of the return value.

Fix: Capture the return value and check it:
  const result = await chrome.cookies.remove({ url, name });
  sendSuccessResult(id, { deleted: result !== null, name, url });

The chrome.cookies.remove API returns a Details object when the cookie is deleted, and null when no cookie is found. The fix is a one-line change.

File: platform/browser-extension/src/browser-commands/extension-commands.ts, lines 151-154 and 258-272.

Bug 1 (line 151-154): handleExtensionGetSidePanel creates a setTimeout in a Promise.race without storing the timeout ID. When sendMessage resolves first, the 3-second timer (SIDE_PANEL_TIMEOUT_MS) is never cleared.

Bug 2 (lines 258-272): handleExtensionCheckAdapter's isReady probe creates a setTimeout in a Promise.race without storing the timeout ID. When executeScript resolves first, the 5-second timer (IS_READY_TIMEOUT_MS) is never cleared. This runs per matching tab.

Fix approach: Follow the same pattern used in dispatch-helpers.ts (executeWithTimeout, lines 56-84). Store the timeout ID and clear it in a finally block:

For handleExtensionGetSidePanel (lines 151-154):
let timeoutId: ReturnType<typeof setTimeout> | undefined;
const timeoutPromise = new Promise<null>(resolve => {
  timeoutId = setTimeout(() => resolve(null), SIDE_PANEL_TIMEOUT_MS);
});
try {
  sidePanelResult = await Promise.race([sendPromise, timeoutPromise]);
} finally {
  clearTimeout(timeoutId);
}

Same pattern for the isReady probe in handleExtensionCheckAdapter (lines 258-272).
